            <p>After internalizing these notes, you should be able to:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Explain</strong> the CPU caching visibility problem precisely: why a write by one thread may never become visible to another thread without explicit synchronization, and why this bug is non-deterministic and environment-dependent</li>
                <li><strong>Apply</strong> <code>volatile</code> correctly to guarantee visibility of simple flag/reference reads and writes, and explain the memory barrier semantics it inserts (<code>StoreStore</code>/<code>StoreLoad</code>)</li>
                <li><strong>Identify</strong> the single most common <code>volatile</code> misconception — that it makes compound operations like <code>counter++</code> atomic — and explain precisely why it does not</li>
                <li><strong>Implement</strong> the cooperative cancellation pattern (volatile boolean flag, checked in a loop) for stopping a thread, and explain why <code>Thread.stop()</code> is deprecated and unsafe</li>
                <li><strong>Use</strong> <code>AtomicInteger</code>/<code>AtomicLong</code>/<code>AtomicReference</code> for lock-free atomic compound operations, and explain the CAS (Compare-And-Swap) mechanism that makes this possible without locking</li>
                <li><strong>Distinguish</strong> when <code>volatile</code> alone is sufficient (single read/write) versus when you need an atomic class (compound read-modify-write) versus when you need full locking (multiple related variables updated together)</li>
                <li><strong>Identify</strong> the pitfall of marking a reference <code>volatile</code> and assuming the referenced object's internal state is also protected (e.g., <code>volatile List</code> does not make <code>.add()</code> thread-safe)</li>
                <li><strong>Rank</strong> plain field, <code>volatile</code>, atomic classes (CAS), and <code>synchronized</code>/<code>ReentrantLock</code> by relative performance cost, and explain the hardware-level reason for each tier</li>
